les, but also had a very real impact at the level of policy, shaping how the Venetian state governed minority populations in the city and its empire. In contrast with the familiar image of ethnography as the product of overseas imperial and missionary encounters, the book points to a more complicated set of origins.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmbassadorszItalyzVenicexCorrespondence. 0aEthnologyzItalyzVenicexHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aethnographic writing, world history, literary studies, cultural studies, Renaissance studies, Venetian Renaissance, early modern studies, early modern Europe, early modern Venice, early modern Venetian state, early modern Venetian empire, sixteenth-century studies, seventeenth-century studies, sixteenth-century Europe, seventeenth-century Europe, seventeenth-century Venice, sixteenth-century Venice, anthropology, ethnography, ethnographic description, Venetian ethnography, cross-cultural contact, cross-cultural encounter, religious divisions, ethnic divisions, linguistic divisions.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978164453303140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644533031423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781644533031/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles